UnityJavaScriptDefold <pre><code>var items = await PortalSDK.GetShopItems();
</code></pre> <pre><code>const response = await PortalSDK.getShopItems();
</code></pre> <pre><code>portalsdk.get_shop_items(function(self, data) end)
</code></pre> <p><code>ShopItem</code> has the same fields as in the admin, and the most important is the <code>id</code></p> UnityJavaScriptDefold <pre><code>public class ShopItem
{
    /// &lt;summary&gt;
    /// The unique identifier of the shop item.
    /// &lt;/summary&gt;
    public int id;

    /// &lt;summary&gt;
    /// The name of the shop item.
    /// &lt;/summary&gt;
    public string name;

    /// &lt;summary&gt;
    /// The description of the shop item.
    /// &lt;/summary&gt;
    public string description;

    /// &lt;summary&gt;
    /// The price of the shop item.
    /// &lt;/summary&gt;
    public int price;

    /// &lt;summary&gt;
    /// The date and time when the shop item was created.
    /// &lt;/summary&gt;
    public DateTime created;

    /// &lt;summary&gt;
    /// The date and time when the shop item was last updated.
    /// &lt;/summary&gt;
    public DateTime updated;
}
</code></pre> <pre><code>interface ShopItem {
    id: number;
    name: string;
    description: string;
    price: number;
    created: string;
    updated: string;
}
</code></pre> <pre><code>local shopItem = {
    id = 1,
    name = "Sample Item",
    description = "This is a sample shop item.",
    price = 100,
    created = "2025-06-12T10:00:00Z",
    updated = "2025-06-12T12:00:00Z"
}
</code></pre>

UnityJavaScriptDefold <pre><code>var purchased = await PortalSDK.GetPurchasedShopItems();
</code></pre> <pre><code>const purchased = await PortalSDK.getPurchasedShopItems();
</code></pre> <pre><code>portalsdk.get_purchased_shop_items(function(self, result)
    -- purchased shopItems
end)
</code></pre> <p>It gives you all the purchased items by the current player.  Now you can display your shop screen and associate your items with <code>ShopItems</code> from the API and mark purchased it.</p> <p>If your item can be purchased infinitely, you can just not mark it. SDK API does not limit you in the number of purchased items per player. </p>

UnityJavaScriptDefold <pre><code>var result = await PortalSDK.OpenPurchaseConfirmModal(itemId);
if (result is { IsSuccessful: true }) {
    Debug.Log("Purchase successful!")
}
else {
    Debug.Log("Purchase failed.")
}
</code></pre> <pre><code>const shopItems = await PortalSDK.getShopItems();

const shopItem = shopItems.find(item =&gt; item.id === itemId)

const result = await PortalSDK.openPurchaseConfirmModal(shopItem);

if(result.status === "success") {
    console.log("Purchase successful!")
} else {
    console.log("Purchase failed.")
}
</code></pre> <pre><code>portalsdk.open_purchase_confirm_modal(itemId, function(self, result)
    if result.status == "success" then
        print("Purchase successful!")
    else
        print("Purchase failed.")
    end
end)
</code></pre> <p>After player will see modal window:    If a user doesn't have enough balance, a top-up popup will be shown    If the player confirms a purchase, after all, you will get the response <code>IsSuccessful = true</code> or <code>status == "success"</code></p>
